## 📝 Interview Questions

**Q1. What is the difference between `textContent` and `innerHTML`?**
> `textContent` sets or gets plain text — HTML tags are treated as literal characters. `innerHTML` parses HTML. `textContent` is safer and faster for plain text; `innerHTML` should never be used with user input due to XSS (Cross-Site Scripting) risks.

**Q2. What is XSS and how does `innerHTML` relate to it?**
> XSS (Cross-Site Scripting) is a security vulnerability where malicious scripts are injected into a page. Using `innerHTML` with unvalidated user input can execute injected `<script>` tags or event handlers. Always use `textContent` for user-provided text.

**Q3. What is the difference between using `style` directly and `classList`?**
> `style` sets inline styles which are hard to maintain and override. `classList` adds/removes CSS classes — keeping styles in CSS files, making code cleaner, reusable, and easier to manage with specificity.

**Q4. What is the difference between `append()` and `appendChild()`?**
> `appendChild()` accepts only a single Node. `append()` accepts multiple Nodes and strings, and has no return value. `append()` is more flexible and modern.

**Q5. What does `insertAdjacentHTML` do and why is it useful?**
> It parses an HTML string and inserts it at a specific position relative to the element: `beforebegin`, `afterbegin`, `beforeend`, `afterend`. It's faster than `innerHTML +=` because it doesn't re-parse the entire element.

**Q6. How do you access `data-*` attributes in JavaScript?**
> Via the `dataset` property. `<div data-user-id="5">` is accessed as `el.dataset.userId` (kebab-case becomes camelCase automatically).

**Q7. What is `cloneNode(true)` vs `cloneNode(false)`?**
> `cloneNode(false)` clones only the element itself (no children). `cloneNode(true)` performs a deep clone — including all child elements and their content. Note: event listeners attached via `addEventListener` are NOT copied.

